english:
  title: Inscription for the Hall of Bamboo and Moon
  author: Byeon Gyel-lyang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Royal Prince, in his gracious wisdom, inscribed these three characters—'Hall of Bamboo and Moon'—and bestowed them upon the Venerable Seonsu. The monk brought them to me and requested an inscription. Thus I offer this:

    Bamboo stands hollow,
    its emptiness complete.
    Moon shines luminous,
    its clarity supreme.
    The master names his hall
    by these two virtues—
    stillness and awakening.

    In the clear discourse of the study,
    the Prince himself has wielded his brush,
    three characters suffused with grace,
    their radiance piercing the heavens.

    Such honor graces the temple gate,
    rare in all the world.
    How can one repay such blessing?
    Only with prayers for the Prince's eternal fortune.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Hall of Bamboo and Moon' (竹月軒) represents a meditation space, where bamboo symbolizes emptiness and the moon symbolizes illumination—key concepts in Buddhist practice.
  - key: ''
    value: The inscription celebrates both the artistic merit of the Prince's calligraphy and the honor bestowed upon the temple through his patronage.
